</meta></frontmatter> <mainmatter/> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>1011</anchor>  <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>axt-003E</addr>  <route>axt-003E.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>11</month> <day>6</day></date> <authors><author><link href="brian-davey.xml" type="local">Brian A. Davey</link></author><author><link href="hilary-priestley.xml" type="local">Hilary A. Priestley</link></author> </authors> <title><tex>\mathsf{(AC)}</tex> implies <tex>\mathsf{(ZL)''}</tex></title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  If <link href="axt-003D.xml" type="local" title="Axiom of choice in set theory"><tex>( \mathsf{AC} )</tex></link> holds then <link href="axt-003A.xml" type="local" title="Alternative formulation of Zorn’s Lemma"><tex>\mathsf{(ZL)''}</tex></link> holds.
</p>      <block open="open"><headline><b>Proof</b>.</headline> <p>  Assume that <link href="axt-003D.xml" type="local" title="Axiom of choice in set theory"><tex>( \mathsf{AC} )</tex></link> holds and let <tex>(D,  \sqsubseteq )</tex> be a
  <link href="axt-003B.xml" type="local" title="Pointed dcpo">pointed dcpo</link>. Suppose that every element of <tex>D</tex> fails to be
  maximal. This is to say that for every <tex>x  \in  D</tex>, the set
  <tex>\{  y  \in  D  \mid  x &lt; y  \}</tex> is nonempty.
</p><p>  This means that the family <tex>\{   \{  y  \in  D  \mid  y&gt; x  \}   \} _{x  \in  D}</tex>  is nonempty. By <link href="axt-003D.xml" type="local" title="Axiom of choice in set theory"><tex>( \mathsf{AC} )</tex></link>, there exists a choice function
  <tex>F : D  \to  D</tex>. This function is clearly inflationary by construction.
</p><p>  By the <link href="axt-003F.xml" type="local" title="Pointed dcpo fixed point theorem III">Pointed Dcpo Fixed Point Theorem II</link>, <tex>F</tex> must have a least
  fixed point <tex>\mu ( F )</tex> satisfying <tex>F( \mu ( F ) ) =  \mu ( F )</tex>. This contradicts
  the fact that <tex>x &lt; F(x)</tex> for every <tex>x  \in  D</tex>.
</p></block>  </mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>